[1]
Date: Mon 8 Aug 2022
Source: Infosalus [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
https://www.infosalus.com/actualidad/noticia-sanidad-confirma-dos-nuevos-casos-febre-hemorragica-crimea-congo-ellos-deceased-pasado-junio-20220808132759.html


The Ministry of Health has confirmed 2 new cases of Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF) in 2 men -- one of them deceased -- residing in the Bierzo region (León), according to a new report prepared by the Center for Coordination of Health Alerts and Emergencies.

The 1st case is a 49-year-old hunter with a history of bites from tick, who began having symptoms on 12 Jul 2022 and is in a stable situation. The 2nd case, aged 51, was diagnosed retrospectively on 20 Jul 2022, after having died on 19 Jun 2022 due to an unknown cause with suspected poisoning by sulfur compounds.

Between 2013 and 2022 a total of 12 cases have been confirmed with 4 deaths in Spain: 1 in 2013 in Ávila, 2 in 2016, one of them in Ávila and a secondary case to this in a health worker, 2 in 2018 in Badajoz and Salamanca, 3 in 2020 in Salamanca, 2 in 2021 in Salamanca and León (el Bierzo) and the 2 that have just been published, corresponding to 2022 and occurring in El Bierzo.

It is not the 1st time that it has been detected in El Bierzo. On 10 Jun 2021, another case was confirmed in a woman resident in El Bierzo who had also been to some places in Ourense, around the Ribera Sacra, Galicia. However, the Ministry of Health affirms that the "risk is moderate" in this area.

For the rest of Spain, the risk is considered "low", although remember that this is conditional on the activity of the vectors, whose activity is maximum in the summer season.

CCHF virus was identified for the 1st time in Spain in 2010, in ticks captured on deer from a game farm in Cáceres, on the edge of the Tagus River on the Portuguese border. A subsequent study carried out in various areas of the country, in different tick species (2053) obtained from livestock and vegetation and serum from people exposed to ticks in Cáceres (114) and La Rioja (114), did not show the presence of the virus in any sample.

In another study carried out between 2011 and 2015, 1579 ticks were sampled in wild and domestic ungulates in Cáceres, Toledo, Segovia and Huesca. Given the detection of the 1st 2 human cases of CCHFv in 2016, a 3-phase study was launched to assess the status and risk of CCHFv infection in Spain.

According to the report on 18 Jul 2022, Castilla y León communicated to the Center for Coordination of Sanitary Alerts and Emergencies and the National Center of Epidemiology a suspicion of (a case of) Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF).

He is a 49-year-old man, a hunter and resident in Ponferrada (Bierzo region, León) with a history of tick bites. On 12 Jul 2022 he began to suffer from gastrointestinal symptoms (abdominal pain, diarrhea and vomiting) along with headache and fever.

On 16 Jul 2022, he was hospitalized with elevation of transaminases and thrombocytopenia. And on 19 Jul 2022, the National Center of Microbiology (CNM) confirmed by real-time PCR the positivity against CCHF virus (CCHFV). The case was transferred on 20 Jul 2022 to the high-level isolation unit in Donostia where he is progressing satisfactorily.

Regarding the 2nd case, the Ministry of Health informs that on 20 Jul 2022 the National Institute of Toxicology and Forensic Sciences sent to the CNM, a positive real-time PCR result against CCHFV in blood. The case reported no history of tick bite, but he had been treating his orchard with sulphate and 24 hours later he began to have symptoms. He was initially diagnosed with respiratory infection with headache; subsequently, he developed abdominal discomfort, diarrhea and on 16 Jun 2022 he was admitted with a severe coagulopathy, experiencing progressive deterioration until his death 3 days later.

As a consequence of this case, 4 contacts were identified in those who performed the autopsy and 4 others who handled the samples in the laboratory. Currently, he has completed the follow-up with no secondary cases detected.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED from ProMED-ESP

