[B]
Date: Sat 6 Aug 2022
Source: Eldia [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
https://www.eldia.es/salud/guia/2022/08/06/crimea-congo-sintomas-tratamiento-73131167.html


Two cases of Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF) have been confirmed in Spain, specifically in the Bierzo region.

He is a 49-year-old hunter who is currently stable. The 2nd, aged 51, died on 19 Jun 2022 and was retrospectively diagnosed on 20 Jul 2022.

Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever (CCHF) is a disease caused by a tick-borne virus.

The infection is caused directly by the arachnid bite itself, or by contact with secretions or body fluids of an infected person.

According to the World Health Organization (WHO), this virus "is one of the 7 most serious epidemic diseases, and represents a great risk to public health."

Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever is of particular concern due to its high lethality in humans to the point that between 10 and 40% of infections end in death, and because of the lack of effective mitigation measures, in addition to no vaccine being available for people or animals.

This pathology -- endemic in Africa, the Middle East and Asia -- has always been considered an exotic disease in Spain.

However, a recent study by the National Center for Microbiology has detected the virus in ticks in 5 communities on the plateau and southeast of the peninsula.

The origin of this investigation stems from the suspicion that the virus was more widespread than previously thought.

Initially, it was believed that the 1st patient diagnosed with Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever was a man who had been walking in the countryside in Ávila.

However, until then, the virus had only been detected in ticks from Cáceres. Therefore, he was not 'patient zero'.

For this reason, a retrospective study was carried out that places the first infection by this virus in 2013.

This is what emerges from the report 'Widespread detection of multiple strains of Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever virus in ticks, Spain'.

Since then, 8 cases of this disease have been detected in our country: 1 in 2013, 2 in 2018, 3 in 2020 and 2 in 2021.

This epidemiological situation reveals a broader distribution of the disease than previously studied.

After analyzing 12 500 ticks obtained from vegetation and animals, the study -- directed by María Paz Sánchez-Seco, head of the Arbovirus Laboratory at the ISCIII National Center for Microbiology -- has confirmed that the virus is present in Andalusia, Madrid, Castile and Leon, Castile-La Mancha and Extremadura.

"The _Hyalomma_ tick is very abundant in Spain and it is very possible that the virus has been circulating for many years. The reason it has now shown its face may be because of the change in the soil, in the farms...", explains Ángeles Sonia Olmeda, professor at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine at the Complutense University of Madrid.

However, despite the fact that the health authorities have sounded the alarm, the researcher clarifies that "this tick does not usually bite people, they prefer animal species to man," she tells Searching for Answers.

"This does not mean that bites do not occur, but they are happening in very specific areas of Spain."

Hemorrhagic fever, which is considered an emerging disease in Western Europe, is accompanied by varied symptoms; fever, muscle pain, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and drowsiness. Severe patients may experience rapid renal deterioration or hepatic or pulmonary failure.

In the case of _Hyalomma_ tick bite infection, the main carrier of the virus (although there are more than 30 species capable of transmitting this virus) and present in Asia, Europe and Africa, the incubation period is usually 1 to 3 days, with a maximum of 9.

However, if it is due to contact with fluids from a patient, the period increases from 5 to 6 days, with a maximum incubation period of 13 days.

With an average mortality rate of 30%, the death of the most severe patients occurs in the 2nd week after infection with the virus.

Eight cases of Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever have been detected in Spain/Valcárcel and Olmeda.

In those people with good progress, the improvement begins from the 9th day of the disease. Treatment of Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever is difficult.

According to the WHO, the antiviral Ribavirin is administered, both orally and intravenously, although it has limited efficacy. Therefore, the way to treat the virus is to alleviate the effects of the symptoms while waiting for the infection to subside on its own.

The specialist is clear: it is not dangerous to go outside or walking in the countryside.

However, it is important "to have that awareness that they have in other countries where there are ticks that transmit diseases."

And for this reason, the 1st thing we must take into account is the type of fabric with which we are dressed:
- Wear protective clothing (long sleeves, long pants, socks).
- Wear light-colored clothing so you can easily spot ticks attached to it.

Regardless of the type of garment, a good exhaustive review after a field day is essential. This review is extended to pets, who must wear antiparasitic collars at all times, which not only protect against tick bites, but also against fleas, mosquitoes or lice.

"It is clear that, if the tick is not attached for a period of more than 24 hours to our body, the chances of transmitting the disease are low."

The Ministry of Health gives the keys to eliminating ticks. Using a simple, fine-tipped tweezers will be more than enough.

You just have to hold the arachnid as close as possible to the surface of the skin with the tweezers and remove it, trying not to separate any part of the body.

"The removal of attached ticks using traditional methods (cotton with alcohol, oil, Vaseline, petroleum, anesthetics, cutting them with scissors, pulling them with your fingers, applying heat, etc.) is not recommended, since they have been considered risky, facilitating the spread of pathogens that they could harbor", officials from the department pointed out.

What happens to pets? The teacher recalls that the use of a protective collar or pipette is the best remedy to prevent tick bites and the lack of it could lead to the spread of Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever.

In humans, he stresses, using "anti-mosquito products" are also effective in avoiding 'frights'.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

[Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever virus (CCHFV) is considered an emerging or even a probable re-emerging pathogen in southern Europe. The presence of this virus has been reported previously in various regions of Spain with sporadic cases reported every year since 2010.

The transmission potential of CCHF in potential hot spots can be reduced by timely identification of the disease and implementation of barrier-protection and patient-isolation practices. The risk of further human-to-human transmission in hospital settings can be significantly reduced by applying timely appropriate infection prevention and control measures.

Furthermore, enhanced awareness of the importance of early diagnosis and laboratory confirmation should be emphasized among healthcare providers in areas with potential circulation of the CCHF virus. Standard precautions, preferably combined with contact and droplet precautionary measures, should be taken when caring for patients presenting with haemorrhagic fever syndrome. Laboratory tests on patient samples present a high risk of transmission and should only be conducted under appropriate biological containment conditions. - Mod.UBA

